{"meta": {"centerNodeId": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "centerNodeType": "taxonomy", "generatedAt": "2026-05-28T16:28:22", "includedNodeCount": 3, "includedLinkCount": 2, "layoutMode": "precomputed-static"}, "center": {"id": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "name": "Carib grackle", "type": "taxonomy"}, "nodes": [{"id": "taxonomy-genus-quiscalus", "name": "Quiscalus", "latinName": "Quiscalus", "type": "taxonomy", "taxonomyLevel": "genus", "summary": "Quiscalus（Quiscalus）是图谱中的分类级分类节点，当前关联6种鸟类，如普通擬八哥、船尾拟八哥、Great-tailed grackle等6种鸟类。", "expandable": true, "memberCount": 6, "x": 430.82, "y": -324.43, "z": -90.1}, {"id": "bird-carib-grackle-a174ee66", "name": "Carib grackle", "englishName": "Carib grackle", "latinName": "Quiscalus lugubris", "type": "bird", "status": "LC", "summary": "The Carib grackle (Quiscalus lugubris) is a New World tropical blackbird, a resident breeder in the Lesser Antilles and northern South America east of the Andes, from Colombia east to Venezuela and northeastern Brazil. There are eight subspecies, of which the most widespread is the nominate subspecies (Q. l. lugubris) of Trinidad and the South American mainland. This subspecies was introduced to Tobago in 1905 and is now common there. Description The adult male Carib grackle is 27 cm (11 in) long with a long wedge-shaped tail, although the latter is not so long as other grackles. Its plumage is entirely black with a violet iridescence, its eyes are yellow, and it has a strong dark bill. The adult female is 23 cm (9.1 in) long, with a shorter tail and brown plumage, darker on the upperparts. Young males are shorter tailed than adult males and have some brown in the plumage. Young females are very similar to the adult females. The seven island subspecies differ from the nominate one in size, plumage shade (especially in the browns of the females), and vocalisations. Breeding The breeding habitat is open areas, including cultivation and human habitation. This is a colonial breeder, with several deep, lined cup nests often being built in one tree. Two to four whitish eggs are laid. Incubation takes 12 days, with a further 14 days to fledging. This species is sometimes parasitised by the shiny cowbird (Molothrus bonariensis), but is quite successful at rejecting the eggs of that species. Behaviour The Carib grackle is a highly gregarious species, foraging on the ground for insects, other invertebrates, small fish, small frogs, lizards, or scraps. It is also known to catch small bats in the air. It can become very tame and bold, entering restaurants to seek food, normally feeding on leftovers. It will form groups to attack potential predators, such as dogs, mongooses or humans, and at night it roosts colonially. Call The Carib grackle's song is a mixture of harsh and more musical ringing notes, with a bell-like tickita-tickita-tickita-ting and a rapid chi-chi-chi-chi being typical. The calls vary in dialect between islands and the bird usually fluffs up its feathers when calling. References Bibliography Hilty, Steven L. (2017). Birds of Venezuela. London: Christopher Helm. ISBN 978-0-7136-6418-8. ffrench, Richard (1991). A Guide to the Birds of Trinidad and Tobago (2nd ed.). Comstock Publishing. ISBN 0-8014-9792-2. Jaramillo, A.; Burke, P. (1999). New World Blackbirds: the Icterids. London: Christopher Helm. ISBN 0-7136-4333-1. Further reading Humphries, M.B.; Gonzalez, M.A.; Ricklefs, R.E. (2019). \"Phylogeography and historical demography of Carib Grackle (Quiscalus lugubris)\". Journal of Caribbean Ornithology. 32: 11–16. doi:10.55431/jco.2019.32.11-16. External links Xeno-canto: audio recordings of the Carib grackle", "shortSummary": "The Carib grackle (Quiscalus lugubris) is a New World tropical blackbird, a resident breeder in the Lesser Antilles and northern South Amer…", "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d0/Carib_Grackle_Male.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-quiscalus", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-quiscalus", "species": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris"}, "expandable": true, "x": 250.42, "y": 332.24, "z": 340.7}, {"id": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "name": "Carib grackle", "latinName": "Quiscalus lugubris", "type": "taxonomy", "taxonomyLevel": "species", "summary": "Carib grackle（Quiscalus lugubris）是图谱中的分类级分类节点，当前关联1种鸟类，如Carib grackle。", "expandable": true, "memberCount": 1, "x": 250.42, "y": 332.24, "z": 338.19}], "links": [{"key": "bird-carib-grackle-a174ee66__belongs_to_species__taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "source": "bird-carib-grackle-a174ee66", "target": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "relation": "belongs_to_species", "label": "属于种", "evidence": "依据 birds.csv 中的种字段补充。"}, {"key": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris__belongs_to_genus__taxonomy-genus-quiscalus", "source": "taxonomy-species-quiscalus-lugubris", "target": "taxonomy-genus-quiscalus", "relation": "belongs_to_genus", "label": "属于属", "evidence": "依据 birds.csv 分类字段补充：Carib grackle 属于属 Quiscalus。"}]}
